iques shows her to have been a serious explorer. His nineteen newly drawn maps make it possible to follow her journey in detail. In her diary Hubbard's full enthusiasm for the Labrador wilderness shines through her descriptions of the great caribou migration, the Montagnais/Naskapi Indians (Innu), and life at a Hudson's Bay post. She also reveals in frank detail the difficulties of asserting her authority as a female expedition leader and her satisfaction at beating out her male rival, Dillon Wallace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh1 aBuchanan, Roberta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHubbard, Mina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357299740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773572997423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773572997/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles